        "contenuto_esteso": "To display this content from YouTube, you must enable advertisement tracking and audience measurement. One of your browser extensions seems to be blocking the video player from loading. To watch this content, you may need to disable it on this site. War on Iran risks emboldening hardliners, reinforcing value of covert nuclear programme Middle East Issued on: 11/03/2026 - 08:38 Modified: 11/03/2026 - 08:44 Annette Young is pleased to welcome Nicole Grajewski, Assistant Professor at the Centre de recherches internationales (CERI), Sciences Po. As a specialist in nuclear strategy, Ms. Grajewski argues the current military strikes against Iran have not fundamentally altered the core reality of the Iranian nuclear program. Rather than eliminating the nuclear risk, the war may reinforce the perception among some Iranian factions that a rapidly deployable nuclear deterrent, potentially pursued through more covert means, provides greater security in an increasingly unstable regional environment. Modern wars grow interconnected as Ukraine and Russia seek strategic foothold in Iran war 11/03/2026 Middle East Trump says US destroying Iranian mine-laying boats 11/03/2026 Middle East 'There's going to be a complete reset of the region at the end of this war' 10/03/2026 Middle East Kharg Island: Iran’s ‘untouchable’ oil artery? 10/03/2026 Middle East Israeli strikes pound south of Beirut, displacing more than 100,000 in a day 10/03/2026 Middle East New footage raises likelihood the US struck Iranian girls’ school 10/03/2026 Middle East Iran targeted by fresh strikes as US warns of 'most intense day' 10/03/2026 Middle East Five Iranian women football players granted asylum in Australia 10/03/2026 Middle East Iran war stifles Hormuz shipping: ‘Unprecedented’ impact on oil & global economy 10/03/2026 Middle East"
